# Intuition
First thought was to sort and compare.
And yeah it worked for me.

# Approach
- Sort both the strings.
- Use two pointers one for ransomNote and another one for magazine.
- Run a while loop with condition that the pointers are inside the strings for both the ransomNote and magazine.
- Inside while loop check if ransomNote[i]==magazine[j] if yes{ i++;j++}
- Else if(ransomNote[i]>magazine[j]){j++;}  // means we are checking if the next char in magazine is equal to the char of ransomNote
- else return false.
- return true if(i==ransomNote.length(); // as ransomNote can be made fully using magazine.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(nlogn) // using sort 

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool canConstruct(string ransomNote, string magazine) {
        sort(ransomNote.begin(),ransomNote.end());
        sort(magazine.begin(),magazine.end());
        int i=0, j=0;
        while(i<ransomNote.length() && j<magazine.size())
        {
            if(ransomNote[i]==magazine[j])
            {
                i++;
                j++;
            }
            else if(ransomNote[i]>magazine[j]) 
            {
                j++;
            }
            else return false;
        }
        return i==ransomNote.size();
    }
};
