---------------------------------------------------------------

**2nd Approach** is a bit intuitive and a very good concept of DP is used here. 
The concept of **Longest Common Subsequence** is used but for which first we need to sort both the strings.

For exp :

s1 = aab
s2 = baaa

After Sorting

s1 = aab
s2 = aaab

Now Find the LCS which in this case will be '***aab***' which is nothing but the entire string s1.
So at the end we are required to check whether the length of LCS is equal to s1 if yes then return *true,* otherwise *false*.

Now let's see the code :
```
		//Using LCS
        int n=x.size(),m=y.size();
        string s;
        sort(x.begin(),x.end());
        sort(y.begin(),y.end());
        int dp[n+1][m+1];
        for(int i=0;i<=n;i++)dp[i][0]=0;
        for(int i=0;i<=m;i++)dp[0][i]=0;
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            for(int j=1;j<=m;j++){
                if(x[i-1]==y[j-1])dp[i][j]=1+dp[i-1][j-1];
                else {
                    dp[i][j]=max(dp[i][j-1],dp[i-1][j]);
                }
            }
        }
        return (dp[n][m]==n);
```

